        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Huxley refers to his article ‘Mr. Darwin’s critics’, in the <hi rend="italic">Contemporary Review</hi> (T. H. Huxley 1871b).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Huxley refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2357.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Joseph Dalton Hooker</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Huxley compares his attack on <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3350.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">St George Jackson Mivart</ref> to Saul and the Israelites’ slaughter of their enemies the Amalekites in 1 Samuel 15: 2–7.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2727.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">James Thomas Knowles</ref> was the editor of the <hi rend="italic">Contemporary Review</hi>. Huxley’s article (T. H. Huxley 1871b) was published in the November 1871 issue.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Mivart’s <hi rend="italic">Genesis of species</hi> (Mivart 1871a) was critical of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">CD correctly suspected Mivart of writing a hostile anonymous review of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> for the <hi rend="italic">Quarterly Review</hi> ([Mivart] 1871c; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7958.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. H. Huxley, 21 September [1871]</ref> and n. 6).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">In his article ‘Mr. Darwin’s critics’ (T. H. Huxley 1871b), Huxley took particular care to criticise Mivart’s use of the work of the Catholic theologian <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4609.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francisco Suárez</ref> in <hi rend="italic">Genesis of species</hi> (Mivart 1871a); see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7953.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Huxley and H. A. Huxley, 20 September 1871</ref> and n. 5.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f8">CD added a chapter to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6019.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 6th ed.</ref> to address objections to the theory of natural selection; he replied in particular to Mivart.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f9">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7958.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. H. Huxley, 21 September [1871]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f10">Huxley refers to Plato’s <hi rend="italic">Republic</hi>, in volume 2 of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2616.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Benjamin Jowett’s</ref> translation of Plato’s dialogues (Jowett trans. 1871).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f11"><hi rend="italic">Gaudeamus igitur, senes dum sumus</hi>: Let us then rejoice, while we are old (Latin). Huxley alters a traditional student song. The original opening line is ‘Gaudeamus igitur, <hi rend="italic">iuvenes</hi> dum sumus’ (Let us then rejoice while we are young). Bursch-songs, or <hi rend="italic">Burschenlieder</hi>, are student songs (German).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f12">Huxley refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2478.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henrietta Anne Huxley</ref> and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2479.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henry Huxley</ref>; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7953.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Huxley and H. A. Huxley, 20 September 1871</ref>.</note>
